@node "Introduction" "DazWall - Introduction"

                              @{b}Introduction@{ub}

This is not JUST a wall. This is a wall that beats the crap out of any
other wall around. The development of @{b}DazWall@{ub} involved months and
months of beta-testing and improving.

I wanted to create a wall which is both easy to use and has lots of features.
Besides that, it has to have a killer-design! And to my opinion
@{b}DazWall@{ub} has all of those qualities, and more...

Don't get deceived by the fact that @{b}DazWall@{ub} was programmed in
AREXX. Most arexx doors are slow and crappy, but this one isn't. Ok, it's
not as fast as it should be, but I'll assure you that this is the BEST wall
ever seen on any platform. All the arexx-code is highly optimized for the
best speed possible. Only the fastest routines are used to create the
features you've never seen before in a Wall.

Ok, this sounds a bit 'too good to be true', but install it! Use it! You'll
see...

                                                   Signed: HiFi/Effect

                             @{" Back to Main " link "Main" 0}

@endnode

@node "Features" "DazWall - Features"

                                @{b}Features@{ub}

DazWall has more features than any other wall and even some features
never seen before. Just take a look at the following list:

- Works on virtually @{b}all@{ub} BBS-systems!
  (tested on AmiExpress, SigmaExpress, FAME and Daydream)
- Totally configurable!
  (BorderColour, Strings, Accesslevel, etc. etc.)
- @{"Online configuration program" link "Configuration" 0}
  (Cursor-Controlled and VERY easy to use)
- Very extended @{"statistics-window" link "Statistics" 0}
  (Nr. of Named/Anonymous/Removed tags and Total Tags)
- Top-10-List of best wall-writers
  (Realtime calculation of the 5 best taggers)
- Possibility to remove lines from the wall
- @{"Banning" link "Banning" 0} users by their slotnumber
- Fully cursor-controlled configuration-program and colour-selection
- Named and Anonymous tagging
- Possibility to clear the wall and the statistics
- @{"Word-ban" link "WordBan" 0} option
- and more....

                             @{" Back to Main " link "Main" 0}

@endnode

@node "Requirements" "DazWall - Requirements"

                              @{b}Requirements@{ub}

These requirements are the same for both the /X-version as the DD-version
of DazWall.

- An Amiga                 (Any setup will do I guess)
- Rexxsyslib.library       (Supplied with the DazWall-package)
- Rexxsuppport.library     (Supplied with the DazWall-package)
- 'c:sort'                 (Supplied with your workbench and the dazwall-
                            package)
- RexxMast                 (Must be running, can be found in the System-
                            directory of your bootdisk)

                             @{" Back to Main " link "Main" 0}

@endnode

@node "Installation" "DazWall - Installation"

                              @{b}Installation@{ub}
 
Load your Daydream.CFG in a texteditor and add these lines to the external
commands part:

DOOR_COMMAND.. WALL
DOOR_TYPE..... 1
DOOR_SECURITY. 5
DOOR_EXECUTE.. Doors:Rexx %N Doors:Dazwall/DazWall.dd
DOOR_CONFS1... XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX
DOOR_CONFS2... XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX

Add something like this to your Welcome.GFX/TXT :

˙DDoors:Rexx %N Doors:dazwall/dazwall.dd||

This should do the trick.


   @{b}!! run the door once to create the necessary data- and configfiles !!@{ub}

                             @{" Back to Main " link "Main" 0}

@endnode

@node "Usage" "DazWall - Usage"

                                 @{b}Usage@{ub}

The usage of DazWall is actually fairly simple. Just run the door by typing
'wall' (or whatever you called it..) on the prompt. DazWall will now appear
and 2 files, called doors:dazwall/wall.data and doors:dazwall/DazWall.cfg,
will be created automaticly.

Now you're at the main-prompt of the (still empty) wall. From here you can
press a various number of keys:

@{b}Y@{ub}    - Yes (add a line to the wall)
@{b}N@{ub}    - No (don't add a line and quit the wall)
@{b}?@{ub}    - Information-screen
@{b}C@{ub}    - @{"Online Configger" link "Configuration" 0}
@{b}S@{ub}    - @{"Statistics-screen" link "Statistics" 0}
@{b}<CR>@{ub} - That will result in either a 'YES' or a 'NO' (depends on what
        you've configured as the default answer.)

(or just use the cursor-keys to move the cursor to the desired option...)

If you decided to add a line to the wall, all existing lines will be placed
one character upwards and a new (empty) line will be available for you to
tag on. If you don't want to tag afterall, just press enter on the empty
line and the wall will quit, in any other case just type the thing you had
in mind and press enter when you're done. Now the wall will ask you if you
want to be anonymous or not. If you type 'N' your handle will be placed
right after your tagline, if you pressed 'Y' the word 'Anonymous' will
appear. After that, the colour-selection will appear. Just use the
right/left-arrows to move the cursor and press enter when you've reached
the colour you want. The datafiles will be saved and the wall quits.
CONGRATULATIONS! You've made your first tag on @{b}DazWall@{ub} :) (Wasn't
that hard, now was it? :)

                             @{" Back to Main " link "Main" 0}

@endnode

@node "Banning" "DazWall - Banning Users"

                                @{b}Banning@{ub}

- If yo want to BAN users from the wall, create a file called 'banned.cfg'
in the doors:dazwall/-directory. The first line of this file must be the
number of banned users. The 2nd line (and the lines beneath it) must be
@{b}slotnumbers@{ub} of the users you wish to ban. I didn't use
Username-banning on purpose, because a user could simply change his name to
regain access to the wall. Please note that a banned user still can view
the @{"statistics" link "Statistics" 0} and enter the @{"Online Configger" link "Configuration" 0} (if he has the right access).
He just can't add a line to the wall, all other options are still available.
If you don't want any banned users, just delete Banned.cfg.

                             @{" Back to Main " link "Main" 0}

@endnode

@node "Configuration" "DazWall - Configuration"

                             @{b}Configuration@{ub}

This is the most exiting part of DazWall. There are 2 ways to configure
DazWall: Online and @{"Offline" link "Offline" 0}. The online-configuration is the easiest way to
do it. Just press 'C' on the first question the wall asks and a new window
will appear. It looks somewhat like this:

               .-----------------------------------------------.
               |@{"  (S) = Save/Exit, (Space) = Quit, (CR) Select " link "C_Menu"}|
               ¦-----------------------------------------------¦
               |@{"            Configure BorderColour             " link "C_Border"}|
               |@{"            Strings Configuration              " link "C_Strings"}|
               |@{"                Clear The Wall                 " link "C_ClearWall"}|
               |@{"         Remove Line(s) From The wall          " link "C_Censure"}|
               |@{"    Change default <CR> on first question      " link "C_CRDefault"}|
               |@{" Change Minimum Accesslevel to the Configger   " link "C_Access"}|
               ¦-----------------------------------------------¦
               |                                               |
               `-----------------------------------------------'

... and a blue 'selector-bar' will appear on the first option (or a white
arrow if you only have 2 colours in your terminal- or bbs-program). Use the
up- and down-arrows to move the cursor, 'S' to save the config, 'Space' to
exit the configger and Enter (CR) to select the item beneath the selector.

                             @{" Back to Main " link "Main" 0}

@endnode

@node "C_Border" "Configuration - BorderColour"

                         @{b}Configure BorderColour@{ub}

- A list will appear with the 7 ANSI-colours (White, Green, Yellow, Blue,
Purple, Cyan and Red). Again, use the up- and down-arrows to move to the
desired colour and press enter. The configger-box will immediately turn
into the selected colour, so you can see how it looks. If you've chosen the
right colour, press space to get back to the main menu.

                             @{" Back to Main " link "Main" 0}

@endnode

@node "C_Strings" "Configuration - Strings"

                         @{b}Strings Configuration@{ub}

- A list of 4 configurable strings will appear. The first one is the string
that will be shown at the start of the door. The default of this string
is "Want to add a line ? [Y/N/C/S/?]". The second string will be shown if
the user decided to add a line to the wall (default: "Oh Boy! Make My Day!").
The third line has the default: "Wanna be anonymous?" (speaks for itself)
and finally, the third line will be shown if the user doesn't want to tag,
or didn't enter anything on the prompt (default: "Lamebrain... :)"). Just
move to the line you wish to change and press enter. The line will be cleared
and now you can enter the new string you wish to use instead of the default.
If you press enter on an empty line, the previously defined string will appear
again. Press <space> if you're done with this section.

                             @{" Back to Main " link "Main" 0}

@endnode

@node "C_ClearWall" "Configuration - Clear the Wall"

                             @{b}Clear The Wall@{ub}

- This one speaks for itself. It will clear the Wall.data. Not only the wall
will be cleared, all statistics and logs will be cleared with it. So be
careful with this option.

                             @{" Back to Main " link "Main" 0}

@endnode

@node "C_Censure" "Configuration - Remove Lines from the Wall"

                       @{b}Remove Lines from the Wall@{ub}

- This is a never-seen-before-function. The config-box will disappear and
all the tags in the wall are shown in white with a selector on the first
line. Again, use the up- and down-arrows to move to the line you wish to
remove ('censure') and press enter. @{b}WARNING:@{ub} The line will be
cleared and saved to the datafile IMMEDIATELY, there's no way of getting it
back after you've removed it. Press space when you're done with the
'censuring'.

                             @{" Back to Main " link "Main" 0}

@endnode

@node "C_CRDefault" "Configuration - Default <CR> on First Question"

                 @{b}Change default <CR> on first question@{ub}

- This is a very useful option. Some sysops want the wall to QUIT when a
user presses enter on the first question ("wanna add a line...?"), other
sysops want the wall to take <cr> for a 'YES'. So I made it configurable.
Just press 'Y' or 'N' after selecting this option.

                             @{" Back to Main " link "Main" 0}

@endnode

@node "C_Access" "Configuration - Minimum Accesslevel to Configger"

              @{b}Change Minimum Accesslevel to the Configger@{ub}

- You probably don't want EVERYBODY to have access to the configger. So you
can change the minimum-accesslevel needed to enter the online configger.
Just press the desired accesslevel in 3 digits (like '030' or '255') and
press enter.

                             @{" Back to Main " link "Main" 0}

@endnode

@node "Offline" "Configuration - Offline"

                         @{b}Offline Configuration@{ub}

The second way of configuring the wall is OFFLINE, with the help of a
text-editor (like Cygnus-Ed or something similar).
Just load the file 'doors:dazwall/dazwall.cfg' in your favourite editor. It
looks something like this:

[34m
030
Want to add a line ? [Y/N/C/S/?]
Oh Boy! Make My Day!
Wanna be anonymous?
buttmunch!!
Y

Line 1: The colour of the wall (must be an ANSI-colour-code)
Line 2: The minimum accesslevel to enter the Online Configger (3 digits)
Line 3-6: Speaks for itself; the strings that are used in the wall.
Line 7: The default answer that is used when the user presses <cr> on the
        first question.

                             @{" Back to Main " link "Main" 0}

@endnode

@node "C_Menu" "Configuration - MenuCommands"

                              @{b}MenuCommands@{ub}

@{b}S@{ub}       - This will save the changes you made to Doors:DazWall/DazWall.cfg.

@{b}[SPACE]@{ub} - This will EXIT the configger, or return to the main-menu if
          you're in a sub-menu of the configger. In the first case, if changes
          were made to the configuration, the door will ask you if you want to
          save the changes.

@{b}[CR]@{ub}    - This will enter a subemenu or select a Config-Option.

                             @{" Back to Main " link "Main" 0}

@endnode

